description:
DX AUDIT: handleOperation, handleRandom, and DSCanvas if-chain have default: return prev that silently swallow missing cases. TypeScript catches 2 of 9 required edits when adding a new DS — the other 7 are invisible. This is why developers ship broken DS that silently no-op.

Add exhaustive never assertion to each switch:
```typescript
default: {
  const _exhaustive: never = prev.activeDS;
  return prev;
}
```
Now adding a DS to ActiveDS without handling it in ALL switches causes a compile error.

Requires DST-182 first (derive ActiveDS from DS_CATALOG) for the never check to be meaningful.

Evidence: DX audit error message table — 5 of 6 common mistakes produce zero feedback.

DX AUDIT: Every one of 33 engine files duplicates `let _stepId = 0`, `function step()`, `function resetStepId()` — ~6 lines each, 198 lines total of identical boilerplate. If the step format needs to change (e.g., add timestamp field), all 33 files need manual updates.

Extract into types.ts:
```typescript
export function createStepRecorder() {
  let id = 0;
  return {
    step(desc: string, mutations: DSMutation[]): DSStep {
      return { id: id++, description: desc, mutations };
    }
  };
}
```
Each engine function creates a local recorder. Eliminates global mutable state AND the duplication.

This is a superset of DST-183 (which fixes the bug) — this task also standardizes the pattern.

Evidence: DX audit confirmed 33 copies of identical boilerplate. Agent grep found _stepId in all 33 files.
